onalist narratives of Christianity as a “foreign” ideology that disrupts local communities. Far from being a divisive force, conversion integrates the slum community—Christians and Hindus alike—by addressing hidden moral fault lines that subtly pit residents against one another in a national context that renders Dalits outsiders in their own land."; Read an interview with the author on the Association for Asian Studies' #AsiaNow blog.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristianity and other religionsxHinduism. 0aDalit womenxReligious lifexIndiaxChennai. 0aDalit womenxReligious lifezIndiazChennai. 0aHinduismxRelationsxChristianity. 0aPentecostal churchesxIndiaxChennai. 0aPentecostal churcheszIndiazChennai. 0aPentecostal womenxReligious lifexIndiaxChennai. 0aPentecostal womenxReligious lifezIndiazChennai. 0aPentecostalismxHistoryxIndiaxChennai. 0aPentecostalismzIndiazChennaixHistory. 0aSlumsxIndiaxChennai. 0aSlumszIndiazChennai. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066754740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096363440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520963634423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520963634/original  a978-3-11-066754-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles